  1. (10pts) When you make a histogram without anything in geom_histogram(), R still makes the plot, but will deliver this message: stat_bin() using bins = 30. Pick better value with binwidth. There are two different arguments you can use within geom_histogram():
  • bins
  • binwidth

First, make a histogram of mpg with bins = 4. Try making bins bigger and smaller, and choose a value for bins that you like. After youve done that, describe in one sentence what the bins argument does.

Heres a bins setting I like:

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram(col = "black", fill = "blue", bins = 10) + labs(title = "Histogram of Miles per Gallon", x = "Miles per Gallon")

The bins argument dictates the number of bars (or bins) that are in the graph. [Notice that even though I specified bins = 10, there arent 10 bars on the graph; this is because there is an empty bar around the 28 mark.]

After youve done that: Similarly, make a histogram of mpg with binwidth = 4. Try making binwidth bigger and smaller, and choose a setting for binwidth that you like. After youve done that, describe in one sentence what the binwidth argument does.

Heres a binwidth setting I like:

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram(col = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 2.5) + labs(title = "Histogram of Miles per Gallon", x = "Miles per Gallon")

The binwidth argument controls how wide the bars are. [Notice that you can specify a binwidth less than 1, but you cant do the same for bins.]

For this part, all you have to do is turn in a histogram with a bins setting that you like and a histogram with a binwidth setting that you like (as well as a short discussion about what these arguments do).

After youve made this new graph, answer the following:

  • What did setting breaks = seq(10, 35, by = 5) do to the graph?

This made it so the bars are now constructed to count the number of observations with MPG values within five-mile ranges, from 10 to 35. For instance, the first bar counts the number of vehicles with an MPG between 10 and 15 gallons.

  • Try a few new values of the alpha parameter. What are the possible values you can use for alpha? What happens when you decrease alpha? What happens when you increase alpha? (The code you turn in this problem can use any alpha you want.)

The alpha parameter can range from 0 to 1. When you decrease alpha, the shading becomes lighter or more transparent. When you increase alpha, the shading becomes darker or less transparent. The default alpha value is 1.

  • The two plots you just made should look basically the same. Explain why they look the same in 1-2 sentences.

When we make a barplot, we create a bar for each individual category; when we treat mpg as a category, each unique MPG measurement is treated as its own category and gets its own bar. Meanwhile, when we make a histogram with binwidth = 0.1, each bar has width 0.1; it turns out that, in this dataset, MPG is measured within 0.1 miles:

table(mtcars$mpg)

Thus, once again, each unique MPG measurement will get its own bar.

Problem 2: Estimating Continuous Densities (35 points)

We will again work with the mtcars dataset in this problem.

  1. (5pts) Similar to Question 1A, make a histogram of mpg, but on the density scale. To do this, simply copy-and-paste your histogram code from Question 1A, and add aes(y = ..density..) within geom_histogram(). Then, choose a bins or binwidth you think is most appropriate (similar to Question 1B).
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), col = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 2.5) + labs(title = "Histogram of Miles per Gallon", x = "Miles per Gallon")

  1. (10pts) Now we will take the histogram you made in Part A and add a couple of more components to it. Do the following:

  • Overlay a density estimate on top of your histogram. To do this, add + geom_density() in your ggplot code.

  • Add a rug to your plot by adding + geom_rug() to your code. A rug plot shows where individual values occur just below the x-axis. Rug plots are often helpful when were working with small datasets, where histograms and density estimates often over- or under-smooth the data.

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), col = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 2.5) + geom_density() + geom_rug() + labs(title = "Histogram of Miles per Gallon", x = "Miles per Gallon")

Your final plot should have both a smoothed density and rug added to it.

  1. (10pts) Recreate the graph in Part B, but this time, change the adjust argument within the geom_density() function. Try a few different values, such as 1/10, 1/2, 1, 2, 10. What happens as we reduce the adjust parameter? What happens as we increase the adjust parameter? Pick a value that you think best displays the distribution of mpg; only include that version of the graph in your output for this part.

As we reduce the adjust parameter, the bandwidth of the density decreases, and the density more closely fits the exact input data. As we increase the adjust parameter, the bandwidth of the density increases, and the density smooths over the input data more.

If you read the help documentation for geom_density(), youll find that adjust is a multiplier for the bandwidth automatically estimated in R. For example, this plot uses a bandwidth thats 75% of the estimated bandwidth:

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), col = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 2.5) + geom_density(adjust = 0.75) + geom_rug() + labs(title = "Histogram of Miles per Gallon", x = "Miles per Gallon")

  1. (10pts) On the homework, well explore adding parametric Normal densities to a histogram instead of nonparametric densities. For this part, well explore a statistical test that allows us to formally assess if a variable seems to follow a certain distribution: The Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) test.

Well talk about the KS test in depth on Monday, but in this part Ill give you everything you need to know about the KS test for the homework. The null hypothesis for the KS test is that a variable follows a certain distribution; the alternative is that it doesnt follow that distribution. The KS test is implemented with the ks.test() function. For example, the following code tests whether mpg follows a standard Normal distribution (with mean 0, variance 1):

ks.test(x = mtcars$mpg, y = "pnorm", mean = mean(mtcars$mpg), sd = sd(mtcars$mpg))
## Warning in ks.test(x = mtcars$mpg, y = "pnorm", mean = mean(mtcars$mpg), : ties
## should not be present for the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  mtcars$mpg
## D = 0.1263, p-value = 0.687
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

The resulting very small p-value allows us to reject the null hypothesis that mpg follows a standard Normal distribution. However, this isnt what were most interested in. For this part, change mean and sd such that its equal to the sample mean and standard deviation, respectively, of mpg. Then, interpret the resulting p-value from that KS test.

Note: The KS test is known to have low statistical power. Well talk about this nuance next week.

We see that the p-value is 0.687; thus, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the mpg variable is Normally distributed. This may seem odd, because looking at the above histogram, the variable doesnt look that Normally distributed. This is likely a power issue - we have a small sample size, which leads to low statistical power, and the KS test itself also has low power. As mentioned above, well talk about this in depth next week.

Problem 3: Histograms and Density Plots for Conditional Distributions (20 points)

The upcoming homework will focus on the distribution of a quantitative variable (such as mpg) conditional on a categorical variable (such as gear). In this problem, we explore different plots that visualize the conditional distribution of mpg given gear.

  1. (5 points) For this part well create a stacked histogram, which is very similar to a stacked bar plot. Follow these steps to make a stacked histogram of mpg (stacked by gear):
  • Create a histogram of mpg the typical way, using ggplot() and geom_histogram(). Choose a bins or binwidth you think is most appropriate.
  • Within aes(), set fill = gear.

Note that, in the stacked histogram, the counts are stacked on top of each other. For this part, all you have to do is include the stacked histogram.

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, fill = gear)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", binwidth = 2.5) + labs(title = "Stacked Histogram of Miles per Gallon by Gear", x = "Miles per Gallon")

  1. (5 points) The stacked histogram in Part A technically shows the conditional distribution mpg given gear, but its difficult to see. The reason is that the bars for each gear dont all start at the x-axis. It can be helpful to instead make transparent histograms. To do this, copy-and-paste your code from Part A, and then specify alpha = 0.5, position = "identity" within geom_histogram(). Note that the default value of the position parameter is "stack". For this part, all you need to do is turn in your plot.
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, fill = gear)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", binwidth = 2.5, alpha = 0.5, position = "identity") + labs(title = "Stacked Histogram of Miles per Gallon by Gear", x = "Miles per Gallon")

  1. (5 points) Now well use a conditional density plot to visualize the conditional distribution of mpg given gear. To do this, follow these steps:
  • Copy-and-paste your code from Part A.
  • Change your geom_histogram() code to geom_density(alpha = 0.5).

Feel free to change the adjust or alpha parameters to your liking in order to better display the conditional distributions. Note that not setting an alpha value makes it almost impossible to see the different distributions (try this out in the Console).

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, fill = gear)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5) + labs(title = "Smoothed Density of Miles per Gallon by Gear", x = "Miles per Gallon")
